      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">How Exchange Rates Work: A Beginners Guide</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">July 6, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>When you exchange money for a holiday or see news about a currency "weakening," what is actually happening? Exchange rates determine how much of one currency you get for another — and they change constantly. Here is a plain-language explanation.</p>

      <h2>What is an Exchange Rate?</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">Exchange rate = Price of one currency in terms of another</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">Example: EUR/USD = 1.08 means 1 euro costs 1.08 US dollars</p>
      </div>

      <h2>What Determines Exchange Rates?</h2>
      <p>Most currencies are "floating" — their value is determined by supply and demand in foreign exchange markets. Key factors include:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Interest rates:</strong> Higher rates attract foreign investment, increasing demand for that currency</li>
        <li><strong>Inflation:</strong> Lower inflation relative to other countries makes a currency more attractive</li>
        <li><strong>Trade balance:</strong> Countries that export more than they import create demand for their currency</li>
        <li><strong>Political stability:</strong> Investors prefer stable, predictable governments</li>
        <li><strong>Economic growth:</strong> Stronger GDP growth attracts investment capital</li>
        <li><strong>Central bank policy:</strong> Actions by the Fed, ECB, or Bank of England directly affect rates</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The Spread: Buy vs Sell Rate</h2>
      <p>When you exchange money, you will notice two rates:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Buy rate:</strong> What the exchange service pays YOU (lower)</li>
        <li><strong>Sell rate:</strong> What they charge YOU to buy currency (higher)</li>
        <li><strong>Mid-market rate:</strong> The "real" rate between buy and sell (what you see on Google)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The gap between buy and sell is the "spread" — this is how exchange services make their profit. Airport exchanges typically have the worst spreads (5-10%), while online services offer 0.5-2%.</p>

      <h2>Common Misconceptions</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>"A strong currency is always good"</strong> — Not necessarily. A strong currency makes exports expensive and imports cheap, which can hurt domestic manufacturers</li>
        <li><strong>"1 USD = 100 Japanese yen means USD is stronger"</strong> — No, the numerical exchange rate does not indicate economic strength. Japan simply has a lower denomination structure</li>
        <li><strong>"Rates are fixed throughout the day"</strong> — Rates change every second in forex markets, which trade 24 hours a day</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Tips for Getting Better Rates</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Compare rates online before going to a physical exchange</li>
        <li>Avoid airport and hotel exchanges — they have the worst margins</li>
        <li>Use a travel-friendly bank card with no foreign transaction fees</li>
        <li>When offered "pay in your home currency" abroad, always decline (this is Dynamic Currency Conversion with bad rates)</li>
        <li>Exchange larger amounts at once rather than many small transactions</li>
      </ul>

